#Text=Katherine FitzGerald , Countess of Desmond
#Text=This article is about the Countess of Desmond .
#Text=For the Irish landscape designer , see Catherine FitzGerald .
#Text=Katherine FitzGerald , Countess of Desmond ( c. 1504 – 1604 ) was a noblewoman of the Anglo-Norman FitzGerald dynasty in Ireland .
#Text=English writers of the Tudor period , including Sir Walter Raleigh , helped popularise " the old Countess of Desmond " as a nickname for her , due to her longevity .
#Text=One estimate placed her age at death in excess of 120 years .
#Text=Another ranged as high as 140 .
#Text=Most likely she lived to about 100 . [ 1 ] [ 2 ]
#Text=A recent biography of the countess suggested that Katherine was at least 90 when she died . [ 3 ]
#Text=Life
#Text=Lady Desmond was the daughter of Sir John FitzGerald , second Lord of Decies in Waterford , and Ellen Fitzgibbon .
#Text=She was probably born at Dromana , in County Waterford .
#Text=In 1529 , she married , becoming the second wife of Thomas FitzGerald , 11th Earl of Desmond ( 1454 – 1534 ) , " her cousin german once removed .

#Text= The couple had a single daughter , also named Katherine , and she remained a widow following the death of her husband in 1534 .

column1: #Text=After sailing to Bristol , she walked the road to London with her invalid 90-year-old daughter who she pulled along in a cart .
#Text=In the 19th century it was claimed that this story arose from a confusion with another dowager countess of Desmond , who travelled to London to petition Elizabeth I .
#Text=This countess was the widow of James FitzGerald , 14th Earl of Desmond who had died in 1558 and was the nephew of Katherine 's husband .
#Text=In London , her petition was presented to King James I .
#Text=She returned to Inchiquin and died later the same year .
#Text=Death
#Text=Lady Desmond reportedly walked every week to her local market town , a distance of 4 – 5 miles , even after her return from London in 1604 .
#Text=It was said that all her teeth had been renewed just a few years earlier .
#Text=She died after falling from a tree at the age of about 100 . [ 2 ]
#Text=Historians of the time disagreed as to the type of tree : Robert Sidney stated it was a nut tree , and that she fell , hurt her thigh , contracted fever and died .
#Text=Another attributed her death to a fall while picking cherries .
#Text=She is believed to be buried , with her husband , in a Franciscan Friary at Youghal .
#Text=Clodagh Tait has questioned the generally accepted date of death of 1604 , citing evidence that Lady Katherine may have died as early as 1575 .
#Text=There are two portraits of Lady Desmond whose provenance is confirmed and a third whose authenticity is less well-settled .
#Text=Age
#Text=Raleigh , in his History of the World , maintained that Lady Desmond married in the time of King Edward IV ( 1461 – 1483 ) , making her at least 135 years old at the time of her death .
#Text=She was said to have danced with King Richard III , then Duke of Gloucester .
#Text=In fact , she could not have been married earlier than 1505 , as her husband 's first wife , Sheila ( Gilis ) the daughter of the lord of Muskerry , was still alive in that year .
#Text=The tradition that she died at age 140 was recounted in Fynes Moryson 's Itinerary and Sir Francis Bacon 's History of Life .
#Text=Harington , writing in 1605 , referred to a man who lived longer than 140 years , and to a woman , " and she a countess , " who lived longer than 120 .
#Text=If Katherine FitzGerald married in her early twenties , this latter description would match her . [ 4 ]
#Text=Historian Ian Mortimer asserted that her age was about 100 , making her a rare although not unique centenarian of the Elizabethan age . [ 2 ]
#Text=Portraits
#Text=The text below Nathaniel Grogan 's 1806 engraving of Lord Kerry 's portrait reads as follows :

#Text=Catherine Fitz-Gerald ( the long lived ) Countess of Desmond From an original family picture of the same size Painted on Board in the Possession of The Right Honourable Maurice Fitz-Gerald , Knight of Kerry &c . &c . &c .

#Text=To whom this plate is most respectfully dedicated by his very obedient and much obliged humble servant Henry Pelham This illustrious Lady was born about the year 1464 , was married in the Reign of Edward IV , lived during the entire reigns of Edward V , Richard III , Henry VII , Henry VIII , Edward VI , Mary & Elizabeth , and died on the latter end of James I , or the beginning of Charles I Reigns at the great age ( as is generally supposed ) of 162 years .
#Text=Published as the act directs at Bear Island 4 June 1806 by Henry Pelham Esq.
#Text=On the back of the original painting , stated to have been executed during the Countess of Desmond 's final visit to London , the following appears to have been painted :
#Text=Catherine , Countess of Desmond , as she appeared at ye court of our Sovereign Lord , King James , in this present year , A.D. 1614 , and in ye 140th yeare of her age .
#Text=Thither she came from Bristol , to seek relief , ye house of Desmond having been ruined by attainder .
#Text=She was married in ye reigne of King Edward IV . , and in ye course of her long pilgrimage , renewed her teeth liuice .
#Text=Her principal residence is at Inchiquin , in Munster , whither she undauntedlie proposeth ( her purpose accomplished ) incontinentlie to return .
#Text=Laus Deo .
